description.text:
A posable action figure robot with flashing electronic eyes! This is a fun multi-media project seen in the December 2012 issue of WIRED. Here's how it works:
Buy the necessary electronic components from RadioShack (grab a copy of WIRED to learn more!), download and make the parts listed below, and go find a standard bubble capsule from a coin-operated vending machine for the dome. Modeling by Todd; circuit design by Andres.

• Trim away pads from claws.
  • Solder circuit together as seen in the diagram.
  • Slide in battery pack into place.
  • Take off the red cap and then remove the nuts and washers from the end of the switch.
  • Put the switch inside the body and poke it out through the hole in the front.
  • Slip the switch cross beam into place so that the switch stays in place.
  • Press red cap into M button and snap onto the switch.
  • Orient the circuit board's holes line up with the holes in the body.
  • Slide the LEDs through the holes in the collar.
  • Screw the collar-circuitboard-body assembly together using the screws
  • Snap the clear plastic dome on top.
  • Snap claws onto hands. Some force may be required to get it to snap into place, but the result is a nice gripping claw.
  • Press pin into left shoulder of body, and attach into left upper arm.
  • Press pin into left upper arm, and attach into left elbow.
  • Press pin into left hand and attach to left elbow.
  • Repeat for right arm.
  • Attach left boot to left ankle using pin.
  • Repeat for right boot.
    • For best results, we recommend the following settings. Infill: 5%
    Layer Height: 200 microns (0.20 mm)
    Shells: 2

title: Hummingbird feeder ant trap / ant moat -- Keep ants out of you hummingbird feeders!

description.text:
I decided to refurbish a few of my hummingbird feeders to give to my mother on Mother's Day as she is an amateur ornithologist when not saving lives, and I bought a printer to make useful things. Plus, one can never have too many feeders! The first step in the process---well, the second step after cleaning the feeders that survived the winter---was to make an ant trap/moat to keep the ants away. Drawing inspiration from the many DIY moats one may find when googling the problem, I "designed" this little thing to install on the feeders before gifting them. Why buy a bottle of water or soda when you can just as easily print the thing in biodegradable plastic? A bit of caulk or Sugru is needed to seal the hole that the feeder's wire/hanger passes through. This should keep the feeder functional, ant-free, and will additionally serve as a small bath for the little buzzers. I will post completed images tomorrow...after dark here, and the refurbished feeders are still soaking in the sink. Dimensions:
x: 50mm
y: 50mm
z: 15mm
pool/moat depth: 10mm
wire/hanger hole clearance: 5mm Moving on to bee prevention!

description.text:
Following the news on Macrumors of a 3d-printable file for the iphone 6 being announced for sale, it seemed a bit rich to have to pay for the file in the first place. It's hardly a complicated shape, let's face it, and the measurements are freely available as rumoured. So, here's an OpenSCad file to create one, and the STL file it makes. There are some comments in there, so you can adjust things to your personal rumour preference. And improve it, of course. It doesn't print the expected lump on the back for the lens (that would mean the entire build would be on supports, or it would have to be printed a different way around). Neither does it have an apple logo or some other details that would be nice. Maybe I'll improve it soon, or feel free to do so yourself... After a bit of a problem with the printer, finally got out a low-resolution print successfully. It's a bit lumpy but I suppose that's what you expect with low-res. Perfectly good enough to feel the size, and it's enormous. The photos show the 5.5" (larger) version in black. The screen shot is printed from the image on http://bgr.com/2014/04/09/iphone-6-ios-8-home-screen/ Details are your choice, of course, but there's a page here that shows a suggested layout for the screen of the smaller 4.7" iphone (printed above in white, in standard mode on a Replicator 5G):
http://www.macrumors.com/2014/04/17/4-7-iphone-6-resolution/ SCad and STL files provided for both sizes.

description.text:
Printrbot / Wades / Extruder Motor top attachment mount. This is the top arm of the E body extruder trimmed and flipped.
It is shaped to be vertical, though not necessarily straight up, as motors are in different orientations. This goes harmlessly and tightly into the open space of the E-body next to the gear, using the unused mounting hole of the Nema 17. It is for small self contained attachments that are lite enough not to rattle. If there is a concern of weight, then a counter balance could be added on the motor side. The bottom is square in this design to accomodate any under mounts that might do better with a flat surface. It can be hung down instead of upright, but there is no vibration dampening that you would get compressed onto the motor.

description.text:
What is it?
--
Its an experiment to see if we can drive a large number of extruders from just two motors and one of the common circuit boards which are only capable of driving at most two motors.
In the SCAD files for this thing you specify the X & Y dimensions of your print bed is and the program works out how many extruders can fit in a housing that will fit on your print bed.
STL files have been included for N=4, other sizes can be generated using SCAD.
Concept
--
If you use one motor to select an extruder and the other motor to drive the selected extruder, then you're not limited by number of motors but by how many extruders you can squeeze on to your print bed. Such a mechanism would be way too large to fit on the x-carriage so this is all intended to use bowden tubes to get to the hot-end on the X-carriage.
For this to be entirely useful, it will also be necessary to build a conjoined hot-end. (I've found that most of my ABS varieties print at similar temperatures therefore using a shared heating element seems feasible, worst case using two conjoined hot ends at different temperatures if the temperature variations are too wide).
Why?
--
So... I can print all the things.
Cautions / Warnings
--
  • So far all I've done is a proof-of-concept design and verify that the resulting STL's are slice-able, this will most definitely change once I start printing it..
  • This approach seems a bit too obvious to not have been done before, I expect that there must be a catch as to why I can't find an existing design. (Translation: I'm not convinced yet that this will actually work, but I don't see any reason it wouldn't work).
  • I'm publishing this as a draft because my primary interest is in seeing printers that can handle a variety of materials in a single print, even if this is not successful it might give others ideas.
  • This thing will stay draft until I've verified it is operational, if anyone else does decide they want to join the experiment, please give me feedback on any flaws you find.
  • If anyone does want to collaborate on this thing then let me know and I'll throw the code on github.
  • If you try to render all the parts OpenSCAD will colapse in a heap, use the PrintPlates to get parts for printing..

Extruder Unit Ingredients (multiply by number of bays):
--
  • 1 Extruder Body (Currently needs bridge support)
  • 1 Tensioner Arm
  • 1 Clutch
  • 1 Extruder Unit Gear
  • 60mm x M8 Hobbed Bolt (I used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:151669 to make mine, and because I was too impatient to wait for parts I also used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:313437, surprisingly it worked).
  • 3 608 Bearings
  • 2 compression springs
    Housing Ingredients (One Set Required):
    --
  • 1 Housing Body
  • 1 Housing Lid
  • 2 Gear braces
  • 1 Drive Gear
  • 1 Extruder Selection Gear
  • 608 bearings (2 x number of bays)
  • M3 bolts (to hold the lid together 1 x number of bays)
    M8 bolts (> 20mm in length to secure the housing to a suitable base on the printer - 1 x number of bays).
    • Print Considerations:
    --
  • The Housing body and drive gear will be a very large prints, rafting will probably be required to prevent warping.
    Known Design Issues/planned revisions:
    --
  • The CAM system might encounter too much friction, may need to adjust to use a bush or bearing.
  • The gear ratio hasn't been a focus in design so far, initially just getting a working gear framework has been the priority, fortunately gear ratio is easy to change by adjusting the height of the hobbed bolt in the extruder bay).
  • The teeth on the gears are only approximating Involute, this could do with refinement in the coding.

I am using a Prusa Mendel I3 variant - Looks something like like http://reprap.org/wiki/File:I3-boxframe.jpghttp://reprap.org/wiki/File:I3...
I had been thinking that the whole extruder head would be mounted on the X, carriage, but as a bowden style extruder setup would work just fine and be easy to do. It would make mounting this system much easier, and reduce the weight and inertia of the X carriage.
Since I have a box frame style, the mount would be simple. I would use a hole saw to make a spot for for the bowden tubes to drop down, and screw the base of the extruder system to the top of the wood. I might want standoffs so there is a gap I can look through to see if things are moving (and to ensure all gears are clear of the frame). Going to a bowden system also has the effect of removing one more set of wires from heading to the X axis.
I think if it went micro-switch, it would be good to add an LED for each drive, so that you can see at a glance from a distance which one is running. It would just be in series with the switch, so no problem there.
With respect to the locking mechanism, I don't think the ABS on ABS will be an issue. The guide hole is pretty tight on the filament, so if you push the filament perpendicular to the drive direction somewhere close to the top feed hole, it wouldn't take any more pressure than the spring for the cam follower would provide. That being said, on a bowden system it probably won't matter as much: The filament off the reel isn't getting dragged everywhere by the X and Z axes. I suppose there is some flex in the bowden tubes, but I suspect that the inherent friction and the fact that the tubes maintain a constant distance between the extruder and the hot end should limit the problem.

title: FasTrak Pass Enclosure Case (San Francisco Bay Area)

description.text:
I designed this case for my FasTrak pass circuit board because I was really sick of seeing the ugly bulky putty-colored block on my dashboard.
This new case is designed to blend in with most dashboard features.
Note that there's no bottom half for this enclosure because it really isn't needed.  This enclosure is really just a cover for the FasTrak circuit board.
Enjoy!

1.)  Crack open the original enclosure on your FasTrak transponder and remove the circuit board (yes, this destroy the old case and will void your warranty...so what?)
2.)  Print out this new enclosure (I printed mine in black ABS to match my dashboard).  I would recommend using raft and support.  I think I used 20% fill with 2 shells.
3.)  Use 3M VHB double-stick mounting tape to mount the circuit board into this new enclosure,
4.)  Use velcro or 3M mounting tape to stick the assembly to your dashboard.

comments.text: LOLz that's awesome. BTW, the CHP can give you a ticket for not displaying the pass, but I think they don't care and just watch the lights at checkpoints for cheaters. :)

I really liked the original PSU Mount that I derived this from, but the upgraded design seemed a bit like a Volvo to me. So I sucked it into Openscad and matched up the screw holes, adding in the barbell design I found on a different mount. This PSU mount is stable and strong, but make sure the infill is relatively high for the thinner X configuration. Here's a video of the build: http://m.youtube.com/watch?v=F2RXcn7tK4k

If you intend to mount your PSU on the typical left rear side (or the right front side) of your Prusa Mendel printer, download the STL file and print it out.  Be careful not to home the x-axis at the end of the print because it's relatively tall.
If you want to mount the PSU on the right rear side (or the left front side - unusual, but with reprap you never know), then uncomment the mirror(1,0,0) command near the start of the .scad file.
I found two #8 screws, about 1/2" long, that fit into the holes in the PSU.

description.text: After trying to print a filament spool roller a couple times, I decided that some jobs are still better done in wood.  The result is a quick 'n dirty spool roller that only requires 3D printing small bearing spacers.  Of course you'll also need some wood, a saw, a drill, drillbits, and drill.

Materials 8 bearing spacers (see the file, download, and print
8x22x7 mm bearings (which is Inner Diameter, Outer Diameter, and width)
a 2"x2" board split in half roughly and then cut into shorter sections.
1.5" sheetrock screws Process: Cut the board
Drill holes in the pieces.
Push screws through holes
Put a bearing spacer over the screw.
Then put the bearing on over the screw.
Put a second bearing spacer on the bearing.
Screw the screws into the other block of wood.
Make another one so that you can get your spools of PLA rolling..

For your consideration today, I have a full body scan from my newly upgraded scanning turntable! I've spent the last week fine tuning my thing: Heavy Duty Lazy Susan for Full Body Scanning (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:28454). In this update, I added a rotisserie motor to power it and am very pleased with the results! The slow, consistent rotation has yielded vastly better scans than before. I got inspired to upgrade my turntable because last week I was asked to review Lenovo's new Yoga 13 computer. I thought it would be cool to try using it as a portable scanning station, but wasn't able to get ReconstructMe running under the prerelease Windows 8. I ended up trying to scan the machine instead. (See my review here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pwVTEg5Nq4Q) Anyways, I created this scan using my newly upgraded turntable- The technique is to start at the bottom and slowly move the kinect up the body. This assures clean geometry from the bottom up.. From there its just a few minutes of cleanup in Netfabb and you're ready to print. video of printing:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jdgzm2R-p_k Look for more full body scans soon!

I found the chin prints a little funky- my first print looked like a zombie chewed the face off. Second time, I printed with no support, but used a pencil as support for a couple layers just as the chin started. I'm pleased with the result. Next time I will have them keep their chin up  a little more during the scan.

description.text:
A belt made by Philippe Kervizic our Business Developer
" Few days ago, i was watching tv and a guy was wearing a 3d printed belt. I felt it was so cool that I wanted to design mine. Here it is!
I am wearing it for sevral days, it is confortable and I didn't get any weakness issue so far. The closing system is still to be improved to make it easier to use (buckle shouldn't be totally removable), but it works fine." Note from the creative director :
Two months ago, Philippe knew nothing about 3D modeling. He had absolutely zero base on design. He taught himself how to use 3D softwares and he now creates some trully amazing models for our MakerBot Farm. We have quite a unique Business Developer at le FabShop!

Printing:
Printed with a MakerBot Replicator 2, standard mode for all parts, no support and no raft (except for dowels)
  • print as many crosses, crosses with holes, H, H with holes as you need according to the length you want for your belt.
  • print one of all other parts
  • print as many dowels as needed, lying on a raft. Layers have to match the length of the dowels to optimise the resistance.
  • mind that the front side of the buckle isn't flat. You want to print it lying on back side.
    • Assembly:
    Assemble the parts this way: ending, cross_hole, H_hole,....., cross, H,....,H, cross_male, peack
    You will need a small harmer to push carefully the dowels into the H together with a cross. The dowel will be strongly fixed with the H but the cross will be free to turn around. Once you wear the belt, cross_male goes into a hole and the buckle slips to get the 2 layers fixed together. In the beginning the buckle is a bit hard to slip but it gets quickly easy to use.

title: Printable Ball Bearings
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
So I found a way to print some bearings up. I am working on a project that requires alot of bearings. But I was annoyed that I can\'t print any bearings for the project. 
I use the filament itself as the ball bearings. But since the filament is a rod the bearing is a little tall. You need to make sure that you cut the rod to the right size, if they are a little too long, they will rub on the end caps. If they are short, they will rotate sideways and jam up the whole bearing.
When I was trying the first design the bearing was spinning, but not loose. So I ran it on a tamaya gearbox to break it in. After about an hour of spinning on that I got a fine white abs powder inside and it was running much smoother. After it broke in, I cleaned the powder and filled it with Vaseline. 
Then it was perfectly smooth.

description.text: This is a collaboration with Tim Pool http://timcast.com and Geoff Shively twitter.com/Jiraffa. They use 3G hotspots for live video streaming and they often overheat and stop working, so they wanted some way to cool the hotspot. So we sat down and designed this thing in less than an hour and printed it out for testing the next day. Rapid prototyping FTW! This thing is a holder which allows you to attach a standard 80mm computer fan to the hotspot for cooling. The prototype has been used covering both the Republican and Democratic national conventions during the heat of summer and seems to work pretty well. A few notes: The grid on the bottom doesn't need to be so tight, and only serves to block airflow. My next revision will make fewer larger holes. The grid doesn't actually need to be there at all unless you need to protect the hotspot from foreign objects. The smaller holes in the middle of each side were intended for a setscrew to hold the hotspot in place, but I don't think they're necessary. You can hold it all together with tape or rubber bands. Most everything is adjustable in the OpenSCAD file, but has not been tested for extreme values.

Print with support. Insert hotspot. This was designed for the AT&T Elevate 4G hotspot - http://www.att.com/shop/wireless/devices/sierrawireless/att-mobile-hotspot-elevate-4g-aircard-754s-black.html
The model may need adjustments to accomodate other hotspots. Attach a standard 80mm fan (Radio Shack 273-243 was used - http://www.radioshack.com/product/index.jsp?productId=2102826 - but any computer fan should work). Attach with M3 or similar bolts. Fan should output air away from the holder (drawing air from the other side, increasing airflow over hotspot. Power with 12v battery (Energizer Xpal 1800 was used, with connector added for the hotspot and fan). Two side slots will be used for the hotspot. One side slot is open for connectors (power, antenna, etc). The other side slot is just for symmetry and flexibility and can be taped over or left open.

description.text:
This is a key to override the safety gate on UK style (Type G) sockets.  
Usually a safety gate requires a plug to have a ground pin to open the safety gate. This prevents users from plugging in a European style plug (Type C) into the socket.  
This key is inserted into the ground pin socket to open the gate.  
Run a rubber band through the eyelet of this key to tie it to your European style power cables.

I print this key with ABS using default makerbot settings. I like to spray a little hairspray on the heat bed to prevent lifting.  
Print with the flat side down.  
I have not tested this with PLA, so I can only confirm this is suitable for ABS.

Extruder that I made for my Cyborg 3D printer. Uses 12mm shaft and gives very good grip. Pulling force is about 60 Newtons. You will need two 6001 bearings and one 608 bearing.

description.text:
This is a replica of a Holotape/Holodisk from Fallout 3/New Vegas. I based this design on the in game texture as the in game model for this item is just a rectangle. Iâ€™ve tried to keep it as accurate as possible but the only source image is the 128x128 texture which isnâ€™t very detailed so I improvised a little with some parts.
I designed this to fit the 4mm tape found in a conventional audio cassette and to have a fully operational mechanism so it should be theoretically possible to make a fully working player for one of these with a little effort. edit:- just added a new pic of the inside with the tape installed Update:- it Works! sort of, just did a very quick and dirty test with parts from an old walkman and a dirll and it plays, not very well but with a proper player it would be much better. see here http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aM91xYbEtww

Print two of both reel halves and two guides and one of each of the other parts. All parts can be printed without support. To fit together 4 M3 screws are needed (between 6MM and 10MM long). To make the item fully operational as well you would need the tape from a cassette and an extension spring or small rubber band.
